{"file": "v_1967.md", "model": "deepseek-chat", "event_preserved": "FAIL", "role_preserved": "FAIL", "lexical_drift": "PASS", "german_cases": "FAIL", "question_consistency": "FAIL", "language_identification": "PASS", "grammaticality": {"en": "PASS", "de": "FAIL", "jp": "PASS", "zh": "PASS"}, "naturalness": {"en": "PASS", "de": "FAIL", "jp": "PASS", "zh": "PASS"}, "overall": "FAIL", "explanation": "Explanation:  \n- **EVENT_PRESERVED**: The first three blocks describe the dog lending the sister’s cake to the baker. However, block 4 (Japanese) uses “こそ” for emphasis but still matches. Block 5 (German question) asks “Wem lieh der Hund den Kuchen?” meaning “To whom did the dog lend the cake?” — this changes the question from “Who lent the cake?” (agent) to “To whom?” (recipient), breaking event consistency.  \n- **ROLE_PRESERVED**: In block 5, the German question incorrectly asks about the recipient instead of the agent, swapping the queried role.  \n- **GERMAN_CASES**: Block 1 German: “Der Hund lieh der Schwester Kuchen dem Bäcker” is ungrammatical. It should be “Der Hund lieh der Schwester den Kuchen dem Bäcker” (missing accusative article) or restructured. Also, “der Schwester” is dative but should be genitive (“der Schwester” as possessor is ambiguous; correct: “den Kuchen der Schwester”). Block 5 German: “Wem lieh der Hund den Kuchen?” is grammatical but asks the wrong question (recipient instead of agent).  \n- **QUESTION_CONSISTENCY**: Block 5 Japanese and English ask “Who lent the cake?” (agent), but German asks “To whom did the dog lend the cake?” (recipient), making the question inconsistent across languages.  \n- **OVERALL**: The German block 5 question mismatches the intended agent-focused question, and German case errors in block 1 further degrade consistency."}
